\begin_layout Title
Status consumption under severe inequalities 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

- a case study in Tanzania
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
Status consumption is known to be ubiquitous but the role played by wealth
 inequalities and spatial exclusion in status consumption is less understood
 due to the varied contexts of developing countries.
 We develop a model for status consumption considering permanent ownership
 and high quality the primary indicators of status in a framework of intertempor
al substitution.
 Incorporating the opposite effects of peer influences and poverty on status
 competitions in the model, we use the data on durable goods ownership from
 the Tanzanian LSMS consumption microdata to discuss how a segregation of
 overall quality in an environment of price heterogeneity may characterise
 status consumption in a developing economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent research on conspicuous consumption suggests its prevalence in both
 developed and developing economies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019,KausSA,ZahraIndia,JaikumarConspConIneq,FrieheGermany,heffetz_visibility"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The ubiquity of conspicuous consumption implies that consumers must maintain
 a consumption level relative to their reference group level regardless
 of how poor an economy is.
 But since reference groups themselves are subject to spatial and economic
 boundaries, the conspicuous consumption in an economy would also depend
 on the extent to which the social reference groups are segmented across
 the population.
 It is quite possible thus that the demand for certain conspicuous goods
 (not commodities) is completely absent in some reference groups that are
 excluded spatially or economically 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The terminology of goods vs commodities provided by Cramer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CramerIncomePrice1973"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is used throughout the current chapter.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We contend that the relevance of reference groups provides a necessary qualifica
tion to the idea of pecuniary emulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in conspicuous consumption - as the consumers need not emulate the rich
 if their social reference is insulated from the higher requirements of
 income corresponding to a group outside their own social reference.
 In other words, if the status competitions for a group do not include a
 significant number of consumers outside their own reference or peer group,
 the status consumption would be necessarily segmented across the groups
 formed on the basis of a particular social characteristic (e.g.
 class, region, race etc.).
 One may hardly claim therefore that the poor majority in a largely impoverished
 economy observes and emulates the lifestyles of a rich microscopic minority.
 The opposing effects of poverty levels and peer-influences on status consumptio
n have not been explored in much detail in the literature - except some
 related studies on the effects of income inequality on conspicuous consumption
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq,Duesenberry1949,ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
