key "FrieheGermany"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 who observe visible consumption in the regions of erstwhile East and West
 Germany after the economic liberalisation at the end of cold war to test
 if prolonged measures of suppressed incomes can influence visible consumption
 when the incomes rise with economic changes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To explore status consumption in the context of wealth differences and social
 segmentation, we fall back to the notion of how status consumption is used
 to offset existing inequalities in income and economic standing.
 Instead of focusing on the disproportionate demand for signaling-goods
 (i.e.
 conspicuous consumption), therefore we adopt a model based on a social-deferenc
e view of status that has been embraced in many economic studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy,corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The model thus developed considers permanent ownership ( owned long-term
 goods ) and quality consumption as the key indicators of status that offset
 the existing income and social hierarchies.
 If the role of status consumption is to influence a ranking of income and/or
 wealth, it follows that two consumers with the same personal characteristics
 and the same set of needs can compete with each other for status only with
 quality in non-durable consumption and ownership of long-term durable goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We incorporate the effects of poverty and peer effects in the model where
 the consumer obtains utility through her social characteristics, quality
 in non-durable consumption and long-term durable goods.
 The consumption for quality and permanent ownership subject to the heterogenous
 prices are then explored across different age-groups, regions and levels
 of urbanisation in an economy.
 The model endogenises the role that personal characteristics (such as social
 class, level of education) play in status through the ownership of long-term
 durable goods and the constraints on quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While measuring permanent ownership is relatively easy in the empirical
 analyses when the assets owned by consumers are recorded in the consumption
 microdata, the measurements of quality using conventional methods from
 demand literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,NelsonQualityQuantity,McKelveyQuality2011,McKenzie2005,GibsonKimQualityBog2019,DongShonkwierCappsQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 turn out to be less attractive due to their reliance on observed market
 prices of items.
 A workaround is implicitly adopted by the visible consumption studies -
 which focus on items that are assumed to be futile for common use (an assumptio
n attributed to Veblen
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Without an assumption of futility of conspicuous items, the measurement
 of quality derived from an aggregation of items over commodities as separable
 groups
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,NelsonQualityQuantity,McKelveyQuality2011,McKenzie2005,GibsonKimQualityBog2019,DongShonkwierCappsQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 would depend on the observed prices of items.
 While the futility assumption does ensure the separability of demand for
 visible goods, it does so at the cost of limiting oneself to a narrowed
 context of quality.
 We thus avoid making the futility assumption and use a more general notion
 of quality that permits any high-price non-durable consumption or a durable
 good to contribute to status - a notion which we feel is necessary to represent
 the conditions of a developing economy where basic needs are unmet for
 a significant portion of society.
 This notion of quality is measured as the 
\shape italic
excess
\shape default
 non-durable consumption given the cost of basic needs (both external and
 internal) - which are measured in data at a district-level granularity.
\end_layout

