 such as social identity or education.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relevance of social identities in consumption habits has been a theme
 visited by much of the literature in conspicuous consumption (see Chao
 et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chao1998"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Charles et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CharlesHurstRace"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Omori et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "OmoriSmithVisRace"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Kaus
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\series bold
 
\series default
and Khamis et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 The literature in marketing studies has similarly explored identity formation
 with acquired goods
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gierl_scarcity,Eastman1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We suggest that a model that views consumption in the context of status
 as a ranking order based on income or wealth could be used to endogenise
 the role of social identity in conspicuous consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion of status most commonly used in literature - where it is seen
 merely as a long-term characteristics of the consumer - however is hardly
 one that relates consumption with social identity.
 The view of status as a static characteristic - which allows the studies
 in sociology and health sciences to use status as simply a vector education
 or income (see Michelson et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Psake et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PsakiSeidman2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a few examples) - in fact poses a necessary paradox when used in the
 context of consumption.
 If status were only accumulated over a sufficiently long-term, how can
 there be any utility from status consumption? The paradox is resolved trivially
 if one considers that status is subject to change with consumption - just
 the way it is shaped by income or education.
 This dynamic view of status - as provided by Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - has been widely embraced in the economic studies.
 Here, status is viewed as an income-based ranking order that can be altered
 by the consumer with consumption.
 In other words, a consumer achieves status utility through status consumption
 by moving herself up in a ranking order that is otherwise determined by
 wealth and income.
 This is the view used in our intertemporal formulation of status consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we detail the relation of social characteristics with consumption,
 it is worth examining some fundamental questions the above view raises
 on whether the status-indicating goods in a developing country should be
 the same as those that are considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

visible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the developed economies or not.
 As the relative wealth differences are more relevant for status differences
 in the developing countries, the wealth differences could have far more
 weight for status than the limited range of visible items available to
 a consumer in the developing world (where industrial development is concentrate
d into fewer urban areas).
 We find that the presence of wealth differences in the developing countries
 is not always heeded its due attention in much of the literature on conspicuous
 consumption which we have surveyed (except for some studies directly exploring
 the effect income inequality on conspicuous consumption with exogenously
 observed poverty/income levels or GINI indices - see Jaikumar 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Wisman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WismanSavingClassIdentity2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Chai et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In much of the literature, the inclusion of long-term durable goods (e.g.
 housing) in status-related consumption has seemed arbitrary.
 Subjecting status to the intertemporal substitution and considering the
 explicit role of wealth differences on status - could guide the assessment
 of whether the particular long-term durable goods should be viewed as part
 of status consumption in an economy or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coming back to the issue of relating social identity with consumptin, it
 is possible to view the social identities too in the same ranking order
 as of wealth in a model where consumption beyond fulfillment of needs is
 seen as the consumer's attempt to alter the wealth hierarchy.
 However, since social identities (tribes, castes, race etc.) are limited
 to a particular social context, their inclusion in the wealth order poses
 another issue i.e.
 that the competitions to reach a higher status are necessarily segmented
 due to the scope of social identities.
 As a social identity that determines a reference group limits competitions
 for wealth within itself, one can no longer assume that lower economic
 classes would unconditionally emulate the habits of upper economic classes
 (i.e.
 pecuniary emulation as defined by Veblen - see Timothy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for relevance of social identities.
 Also see Frank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Chai
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for an empirical perspective on reference groups).
 This is because a social characteristic could carry some weight or utility
 for a consumer who compares herself to someone outside the limits of her
 social identity.
 It is only outside the reference group driven by one's identity that the
 social identity influences status the way wealth differences would.
 With the scope of the social identity which determines a reference group,
 the social identity doesn't carry much status to those in the reference
 group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since social identities are themselves often a result of long-term economic
 differences, the direction of wealth differences and social identities
 could be indistinguishable for empirical purposes.
 However, this may not always be the case in the economies undergoing fundamenta
l changes where older identities disappear and get replaced by newer ones.
 In a rapidly changing economy, that is, some social identities are likely
 to superseded by economic developments while others may get more crystallised
 - thus complicating the influence of identities on status.
 The combined effect of social identities and wealth differences on status
 is the quantitative concern that interests us in our model for status where
 it is indicated with consumption quality and permanent ownership.
 Before we describe the measurement of the two and explain the model in
 more detail, it is worth reiterating that despite the rapid economic developmen
ts and creation of new markets for status - which often serve as a backdrop
 for visible consumption - it is possible that due to structural inequalities
 in the developing world, the socio-economic inequalities have far more
 weight in certain contexts for status than the consumption of a few conspicuous
 items that are considered visible in the developed economies (see Ustuner-Holt
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UstunerHolt2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for criticism of a certain 
\shape italic
belle epoque 
\shape default
view of status consumption and Khamis et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for how visibility surveys are adjusted for unequal economies 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The questions in the consumer survey 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 (which is how a researcher may obtain the list of visible items) is adjusted
 to include items that may indicate wealth.
 This is because the criteria of what items are of visible importance is
 not enough for identifying status consumption in an environment where wealth
 differences are both wide and visible.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recap, if status is viewed as a ranking order based on long-term characterist
ics such as income, education and other social characteristics, the consumers
 can be assumed to compete with each other in order to offset the deep wealth
 and social hierarchies that determine the ranking order (see Corneo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In an empirical analysis, there are two status indicator variables whose
 measurement is critical to the model's operationalisation.
 First, is the wealth of a consumer which we could proxy relatively easily
 in a developing economy if the stock of durable goods the consumer has
 (inclusive of housing, land and other long-term assets) is made available.
 Second, is the quality in non-durable consumption.
 We consider the contribution of quality to status simply because the fulfillmen
t of basic needs alone is not expected to offer any advantage in a status
 competition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More specifically, a consumer with a habit of 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
high-quality in consumption (or deriving higher felicity above the fulfillment
 of needs) would 
\shape italic
ceteris paribus 
\shape default
have higher status than another consumer consuming less quality.
 Therefore as long as a common set of consumer needs - which are fundamentally
 the same by definition - can be measured in a population being observed,
 there is no status utility to be achieved through addressing of needs alone.
 The claim has a particular implication for our model of utility - if there
 is any status related utility to be derived from non-durable consumption,
 it would be constituted in the felicity from 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
quality (which is defined as distance from needs which themselves are observed
 within a particular reference group).
 It also follows that any status that is not signaled with quality in non-durabl
e consumption and is not associated with the innate social characteristics
 of the consumer, it must come out of the possession of (and thus utility
 from) the long-term durable goods (i.e.
 the proxy of wealth).
 This can also incorporate the life-cycle assumptions if a durable good
 is seen as one that can be passed on to the progeny.
 Stated differently, the long-term goods encompass the long-term demands
 of the consumer while her short-term concerns (which could themselves be
 influenced by the acquired wealth) comprise only of needs and quality (inclusiv
e of short-term durable items - if any).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A robust empirical measure of quality has been subject to much debate in
 the literature owing primarily to the lack of sufficiently detailed consumption
 surveys.
 Most consumption surveys hardly record the market-observed prices or the
 quantities of the items consumed - let alone the brand-related details
 of the items.
 This makes the identification of higher quality somewhat non-trivial.
 The market-prices of items purchases or even quantities consumed - which
 could permit us to view quality as the proportion of expensive items standardis
ed by quantity (see Nelson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Deaton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Gibson et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GibsonKimQualityBog2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and McKelvey 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McKelveyQuality2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) - are seldom recorded in the consumption surveys.
 In the instances where they are recorded, they tend to be limited to the
 food items alone.
 In the absence of quantities consumed and the detailed prices of key diary
 items, we use the notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

excess
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 quality by consider a higher-than-required consumption based on a minimum
